SIMPLE: anthrax
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Anthrax
<hw>An"thrax</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧n"thr⟦acr⟧ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.,
fr. Gr. <grk>'a`nqrax</grk> coal, carbuncle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A carbuncle.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A malignant pustule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A microscopic, bacterial organism
(<spn>Bacillus anthracis</spn>), resembling transparent rods. [See
<xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Bacillus</er>.]</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An infectious disease of cattle and sheep. It is
ascribed to the presence of a rod-shaped gram-positive bacterium
(<spn>Bacillus anthracis</spn>), the spores of which constitute the
contagious matter. It may be transmitted to man by inoculation. The
spleen becomes greatly enlarged and filled with bacteria. Called also
<altname>splenic fever</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Anthrax vaccine</ent>⟦br⟧
